_name=Scientist Supreme\n|real_name=George Clinton\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''Super-Villain Team Up'' #17 (June 1980)\n|creators=[[Jim Shooter]]<br>[[Peter Gillis]]\n|alliances=[[Advanced Idea Mechanics|A.I.M.]]\n|aliases=\n|powers=Genius-level intellect\n}}\n'''George Clinton''' was the second individual to use the Scientist Supreme persona within A.I.M.. Clinton provided the [[Red Skull]], [[Armin Zola]] and the [[Hate-Monger]] with a restored version of the [[Cosmic Cube]]; however, he gets his mind drained (along with many others) by the three supervillains as a power source for the very device that he helped restore.<ref>''Super-Villain Team Up'' #17 (June 1980). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n===Valdemar Tykkio===\n{{Infobox comics character\n| image=\n|caption=\n|character_name=Scientist Supreme\n|real_name=Valdemar Tykkio \n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''[[Iron Man]]'' #201 (December 1985)\n|creators=[[Jim Shooter]]<br>[[Denny O'Neil]]\n|alliances=[[Advanced Idea Mechanics|A.I.M.]]\n|aliases=\n|powers=Genius-level intellect\n}}\n'''Valdemar Tykkio''' was the third individual to use the Scientist Supreme persona within A.I.M..<ref>''Iron Man'' #201 (December 1985). Marvel Comics.</ref> Valdemar had occasional encounters with [[Iron Man]] while dealing with his brother Yorgon Tykkio trying to take his coveted position.<ref>''Iron Man'' #204-207; 215-216 (March\u2013June 1986; February\u2013March 1987). Marvel Comics.</ref> \n{{-}}\n\n===Fourth A.I.M. Leader===\n{{Infobox comics character\n| image=\n|caption=\n|character_name=Scientist Supreme\n|real_name=\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''[[Iron Man]]'' #247 (October 1989)\n|creators=[[Tom DeFalco]]<br>[[Bob Layton]]\n|alliances=[[Advanced Idea Mechanics|A.I.M.]]\n|aliases=\n|powers=Genius-level intellect\n}}\nA fourth individual had used the Scientist Supreme persona within A.I.M.. This Scientist Supreme had a deal with [[Hydra (comics)|HYDRA]] to eliminate [[Madame Masque]], resulting in a confrontation with Iron Man and the [[Hulk]].<ref>''Iron Man'' #247 (October 1989). Marvel Comics.</ref> \n{{-}}\n\n===Monica Rappaccini===\n{{main|Monica Rappaccini}}\nMonica Rappaccini is the fifth individual to use the Scientist Supreme alias within A.I.M.<ref>''Amazing Fantasy'' #7 (2005). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n===Hank Pym===\n{{main|Hank Pym}}\nAt one point, Hank Pym grew to a large enough size where he encountered the cosmic entity [[Eternity (comics)|Eternity]], claiming to the former that he is Earth's \"Scientist Supreme\".<ref>''Mighty Avengers'' #30 (October 2009). Marvel Comics.</ref> When Hank Pym told [[Loki (comics)|Loki]] about this, the trickster god claims he was using Eternity's form in order to trick the so-called Scientist Supreme. Hank Pym disputed Loki's explanation. Whether or not it was indeed Loki-in-disguise has not been answered.<ref>''Mighty Avengers'' #34 (March 2010). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n===Andrew Forson===\n{{Infobox comics character<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''[[Fantastic Four]]'' #610 (November 2012)\n|creators=[[Jonathan Hickman]]<br>[[Ryan Stegman]]\n|character_name=Andrew Forson\n|real_name=\n|alliances=[[Advanced Idea Mechanics|A.I.M.]]<br>Cult of Entropy\n|aliases=A.I.M. Scientist Supreme\n|powers=Genius-level intellect\n}}\n'''Andrew Forson''' is the sixth character within A.I.M. to use the title of Scientist Supreme. The character first appeared in ''[[Fantastic Four (comic book)|Fantastic Four]]'' #610 and was created by [[Jonathan Hickman]] and [[Ryan Stegman]].\n\nForson was the Scientist Supreme of A.I.M. after the organization became public and established their base in the now-sovereign island nation of Barbuda and overthrew the [[Wizard (Marvel Comics)|Wizard]] with consent of the rest of A.I.M.. Barbuba was then renamed A.I.M. Island.<ref>''Fantastic Four'' #610 (November 2012). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nForson appears as the Supreme Leader of the new High Council of A.I.M., consisting of [[Graviton (comics)|Graviton]] (as the Minister of Science), Jude the Entropic Man (as the [[Health minister|Minister of Health]]), [[Mentallo]] (as the Minister of Home Affairs), [[Superia]] (as the [[Education minister|Minister of Education]] in Bagalia), the female [[Black Widow (Yelena Belova)|Super-Adaptoid]] (as the [[Minister of State]] in Bagalia), and the undercover [[Taskmaster (comics)|Taskmaster]] (as the [[Defence minister|Minister of Defense]]).<ref>''Secret Avengers'' vol. 2 #2 (March 2013). Marvel Comics.</ref> Forson then leads A.I.M. into attending a weapons expo, which led to A.I.M. fighting against the [[Secret Avengers]]. During the battle, Forson takes the opportunity to steal the [[Iron Patriot]] armor.<ref>''Secret Avengers'' vol. 2 #3 (April 2013). Marvel Comics.</ref> [[Daisy Johnson]] launched an unsanctioned operation to send the Secret Avengers to A.I.M. Island to assassinate Forson, and the group seemingly killed him. Despite Johnson ending up suspended for breaking protocol and [[Maria Hill]] being put in charge of S.H.I.E.L.D. again, Forson was revealed to be alive all along, and the news of A.I.M. being a new permanent member of the Security Council is known.<ref>''Secret Avengers'' vol. 2 #5 (June 2013). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nForson finds Superia badly injured after an incident on A.I.M. Island regarding an escaped creature.<ref>''Avengers'' vol. 5 #15. Marvel Comics.</ref> An A.I.M. Agent then approaches Forson and Superia, showing the two a 2-D hologram of the organism beating the Avengers. Taking pride in this, Forson orders their translocator activated and to retrieve their \"lost child\".<ref>''Avengers'' vol. 5 #16 (July 2013). Marvel Comics.</ref> When Taskmaster is shot and seemingly killed by Mockingbird now under Forson's control,<ref>''Secret Avengers'' vol. 2 #13 (February 2014). Marvel Comics.</ref> Forson revealed that Mockingbird was secretly working for Forson years ago, and that he used Mockingbird to \"get [[Victorius (comics)|Victorious]] out of the way\" so that he could take over the Cult of Entropy.<ref>''Secret Avengers'' vol. 2 #14 (March 2014). Marvel Comics.</ref> Forson also uses [[Super-Adaptoid|Adaptoids]] from an alternate reality to combat the Avengers.<ref>''Avengers'' vol. 5 #25-28 (January\u2013April 2014). Marvel Comics.</ref> Using an unidentified device, Forson and A.I.M. accelerate the flow of time in the limits of A.I.M. Island, creating in a matter of hours for the real world year of progress and transforming A.I.M. into a technologically advanced empire.<ref>''Avengers World'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> When [[Smasher (Marvel Comics)|Smasher]] comes to the island, Forson has Jude the Entropic Man transform her into his messenger.<ref>''Avengers World'' #2 (January 2014). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nForson is an experienced scientist with genius-level intellect.\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\n* The Lyle Getz iteration of [[Advanced Idea Mechanics|A.I.M.]]'s Scientist Supreme appears in ''[[Iron Man: Armored Adventures]]''. In \"Ready, A.I.M., Fire\", he assists his fellow A.I.M. operatives in building [[MODOK]]. In \u201cDesigned Only For Chaos\u201d, A.I.M. uses the [[Living Laser]] to finish creating MODOK, who murders the Scientist Supreme so he can can take control of A.I.M. even though Getz was planning on doing so anyway.\n* Two different versions of the A.I.M. Scientist Supreme appear on ''[[The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes]]'', voiced by [[Nolan North]] (first iteration),<ref>{{cite web|title=Full cast and crew of ''The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes'' \"Breakout: Part 1|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1699027fullcredits#cast |work=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=2011-12-01}}</ref> and by [[Kyle Hebert]] (Lyle Getz).<ref>{{cite web|title=Full cast and crew of ''The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes'' \"Prisoner of War|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2355209fullcredits#cast |work=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=2012-01-07}}</ref> In \"Breakout Pt. 1\", an unidentified Scientist Supreme negotiates with [[Doctor Doom]]'s agent [[Lucia von Bardas]], before [[Iron Man]] intervenes and captures the A.I.M. agents. They are transferred to the [[Vault (comics)|Vault]], though they later escape off-screen in \"The Breakout (Pt. 1)\". In \"Alone Against A.I.M\", the Scientist Supreme attempts to get revenge via the [[Technovore]], but he is defeated by the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]. In \"Prisoner of War\", Getz is captured and replaced by a [[Skrull]] infiltrator before he joins forces with [[Captain America]] and his fellow prisoners to escape. In \"Secret Invasion\", Skrull Queen [[Veranke]] orders the Skrull impersonating Getz to use satellite weapons to destroy all life on Earth in response to the Avengers foiling her invasion, but [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]] destroys the satellites while the Skrulls are arrested by [[S.W.O.R.D. (comics)|S.W.O.R.D.]] agents.\n* An amalgamated iteration of A.I.M.'s Scientist Supreme appears in the ''[[Avengers Assemble (TV series)|Avengers: Ultron Revolution]]'' episode \"Adapting to Change\", voiced by [[Jim Meskimen]].<ref>{{cite episode|title=Adapting to Change|series=Avengers: Ultron Revolution|serieslink=Avengers Assemble (TV series)|network=Disney XD|season=3|number=1|airdate=March 13, 2016}}</ref> This version has George Clinton's appearance, Valdemar Tykkio's accent, and Andrew Forson's attire. This Scientist Supreme uses three [[Super-Adaptoid|Adaptoids]] to fight the Avengers before merging with them to become the '''Supreme Adaptoid''', only to be defeated by the heroes and absorbed by [[Ultron]].\n* The Monica Rappaccini version of A.I.M.'s Scientist Supreme appears in the ''[[Spider-Man (2017 TV series)|Spider-Man]]'' animated series, voiced by [[Grey DeLisle]].<ref>{{cite episode|title=School of Hard Knocks|series=Spider-Man|network=Disney XD|season=2|number=30|airdate=July 9, 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Video games===\n* A.I.M's Scientist Supreme appears in ''[[Marvel Avengers Academy]]''. While he is the leader of A.I.M., he is also the headmaster of the A.I.M. Institute of Super-Technology.\n* An unnamed female Scientist Supreme appears in ''[[Marvel Strike Force]]''.\n* The Monica Rappaccini version of A.I.M.'s Scientist Supreme appears in ''Marvel Powers United VR'', voiced by [[Jennifer Hale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/video-games/Marvel-Powers-United-VR/Scientist-Supreme/|title=Voice of Scientist Supreme - Marvel Powers United VR (Game) <nowiki>|</nowiki> Behind The Voice Actors|website=behindthevoiceactors.com|accessdate=2018-09-20|postscript=. Check mark indicates role has been confirmed using screenshots of closing credits and other reliable sources}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://marvel.wikia.com/wiki/Scientist_Supreme Scientist Supreme] at Marvel Wiki \n* [http://marvel.wikia.com/wiki/Lyle_Getz Lyle Getz] at Marvel Wiki\n* [http://marvel.wikia.com/wiki/George_Clinton George Clinton] at Marvel Wiki\n* [http://marvel.wikia.com/wiki/Valdemar_Tykkio_(Earth-616) Vlademar Tykkio] at Marvel Wiki\n\n[[Category:Marvel Comics characters]]\n[[Category:Set indices on comics]]\n[[Category:Fictional scientists]]"}]}}}}